<section class="card">
  <h2>About Spinach</h2>

  <p class="tagline">
    Cool-season greens—fast maturity, highly tolerant of cold.
  </p>

  <p class="lede">
    <strong>Spinach thrives in cool temperatures and tolerates light frost.</strong>
    For GrowByDate modeling, frost is defined as 32°F (0°C). In a typical year (1991–2020 climate normals at the 50% probability level), spinach is rarely limited by first frost. Instead, viability depends on fitting maturity into cool windows before heat triggers bolting.
  </p>

  <p>
    In short seasons, spinach is one of the most reliable early crops. Its low heat requirement and frost tolerance provide natural margin, especially in northern climates.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Quick Planning Reference</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Direct sow:</strong> 6–2 weeks before last frost (soil workable)</li>
    <li><strong>Fall sowing:</strong> Count backward from first frost with buffer</li>
    <li><strong>Days to maturity:</strong> 35–55 days (variety-dependent)</li>
    <li><strong>Frost tolerance:</strong> Hardy (handles multiple light frosts)</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="fine muted">
    These are baseline ranges. Heat spikes often end harvest before frost does.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Temperature Profile</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Optimal growth:</strong> 45–65°F (7–18°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Slow growth:</strong> Below ~40°F (4°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Bolting risk:</strong> Above ~75°F (24°C)</li>
    <li><strong>Planning frost boundary:</strong> 32°F (0°C)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Spinach tolerates light frost and may even survive brief dips below 32°F (0°C).
    Sustained hard freezes eventually halt growth, but first frost is rarely the immediate endpoint.
  </p>

  <p class="fine">
    For context on freeze intensity, see:
    <a href="/guides/light-freeze-vs-hard-freeze/">Light freeze vs hard freeze</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Spring vs Fall Timing</h2>

  <p>
    Spinach is well suited to both spring and fall:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Spring crop:</strong> Sow early for harvest before sustained heat.</li>
    <li><strong>Fall crop:</strong> Count backward from first frost and allow buffer for slower late-season growth.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Use the <a href="/tools/first-frost-planner/">First Frost Planner</a> to anchor fall sowing dates.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Typical GDD Requirement</h2>

  <p><strong>Base temperature:</strong> 50°F (10°C)</p>
  <p><strong>Approximate GDD needed:</strong> ~400–700 GDD (base 50)</p>

  <p>
    Spinach has a modest heat requirement. In cool springs, maturity may extend slightly beyond labeled days, but overall GDD demand is low compared to warm-season crops.
  </p>

  <p class="fine muted" style="margin-top:14px;">
    GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − 50
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Use the GDD Planner</a>
  </div>

  <p class="fine">
    For the full frost + heat interaction model, see:
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How frost dates and Growing Degree Days work together</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Minimum Frost-Free Days</h2>

  <p>
    Most spinach varieties reach harvest in <strong>35–55 frost-free days</strong>.
    Because spinach tolerates frost, effective harvest windows may extend slightly beyond first frost in mild conditions.
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Check Your Frost-Free Season</a>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Short-Season Viability Flag</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Good choice under 100 days?</strong> Yes (very reliable)</li>
    <li><strong>Risky under 90 days?</strong> Rarely; short maturity minimizes risk</li>
    <li><strong>Needs season extension?</strong> Usually no; frost tolerance provides buffer</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>First Frost Sensitivity</h2>

  <p>
    Spinach tolerates light frost near 32°F (0°C), though repeated hard freezes can eventually halt growth.
    For planning consistency, treat 32°F (0°C) as the frost boundary while recognizing spinach’s extended tolerance.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Early-Maturing Strategy</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Sow as soon as soil is workable in spring</li>
    <li>Select bolt-resistant varieties for late spring plantings</li>
    <li>For fall crops, allow buffer for slower growth as days shorten</li>
    <li>Use partial shade in warm climates to delay bolting</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Planning Model</h2>

  <p class="muted">
    Frost → Season Length → GDD → Crop Requirement → Risk Margin
  </p>

  <p>
    In a typical year, spinach is viable in most short-season climates because of its low GDD requirement and frost tolerance.
    The primary constraint is heat-triggered bolting, not frost survival.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <h3>Can spinach survive frost?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes. Spinach commonly tolerates light frost and may survive brief dips below 32°F (0°C).
  </p>

  <h3>Why did my spinach bolt?</h3>
  <p>
    Bolting is usually triggered by sustained heat and long days rather than frost.
  </p>

  <h3>Is spinach reliable in very short seasons?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes. Its quick maturity and modest heat requirement make it one of the safest crops.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Use 32°F (0°C) as the frost boundary (50% probability, 1991–2020 normals).</li>
    <li>Spinach tolerates frost and is limited more by heat than cold.</li>
    <li>Typical requirement: 35–55 days, ~400–700 GDD (base 50).</li>
    <li>Model viability using frost window + seasonal heat budget + variety requirement + risk margin.</li>
  </ul>
</section>